          <h1> AAT comments on the ‘Building our Industrial Strategy’ green paper</h1>
          <span class="news-date">Tuesday 24 January 2017</span>
          <div class="news-detail">
            <!----><div class="news-detail--media">
              <img class="news-detail--image" src="https://cms-stage.aws.aat.org.uk/flysystem/articles/news_and_pr-55578.jpg" alt=" AAT comments on the ‘Building our Industrial Strategy’ green paper" title=" AAT comments on the ‘Building our Industrial Strategy’ green paper">
            </div>
            <div class="news-detail--content" innerHTML="<p>The Building our Industrial Strategy green paper has been <a href=&quot;https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/building-our-industrial-strategy&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>published by the Government</a>.&amp;#160;</p><p>The paper sets out a plan to improve living standards and economic growth by increasing productivity and driving growth across the whole country.&amp;#160;</p>&amp;#10;<p>To achieve these goals, the green paper sets out ten strategic pillars.&amp;#160;</p>&amp;#10;<p>Two of these pillars &amp;#8211; developing skills and supporting businesses to grow &amp;#8211; are particularly relevant to AAT, &amp;#160;which already plays an important role in both areas.</p>&amp;#10;<h3>Developing skills&amp;#160;</h3>&amp;#10;<p>The green paper indicates that Government must help people and businesses to thrive by, &amp;#8220;&amp;#8230;ensuring everyone has the basic skills needed in a modern economy&amp;#8221; and &amp;#8220;&amp;#8230;building a new system of technical education to benefit the half of young people who do not go to university.&amp;#8221;</p>&amp;#10;<p>AAT has over 80,000 students of which approximately 16,000 are apprentices. AAT would like to see careers information, advice and guidance in schools and colleges improved so that all young people are aware of the different routes to a rewarding career rather than continuing with the narrow focus on a University education.</p>&amp;#10;<p>Suzie Webb, Director of Education &amp;amp; Development, AAT said: &amp;#160;</p>&amp;#10;<blockquote><p>&amp;#8220;The publication of an industrial strategy is a welcome development. There are lots of practical ways in which Government could better help those young people who don&amp;#8217;t go to University, but improving information advice and guidance in schools would certainly be the most effective. AAT has made a number of recommendations as to how to achieve this, and will continue to engage with Government to push these recommendations forward.&amp;#8221;</p>&amp;#10;</blockquote>&amp;#10;<h3>Supporting businesses to grow</h3>&amp;#10;<p>The green paper highlights a desire to ensure businesses across the UK can access the finance and management skills they need to grow.&amp;#160;</p>&amp;#10;<p>In addition to equipping tens of thousands of people with the necessary finance and accounting skills to make businesses successful, and having licensed accountants provide accounting and financial support services to over 400,000 small businesses, AAT recently launched <a href=&quot;http://www.informi.co.uk&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>informi</a> a web site that provides free practical advice and support for small businesses. This includes information ranging from marketing and HR to accessing finance and improving management skills.</p>&amp;#10;<p>Adam Harper, Director of Strategy and Professional Standards at AAT, said;</p>&amp;#10;<blockquote><p>&amp;#8220;The Government is right to concentrate on supporting businesses to start and grow. The UK already has a great track record at setting up new businesses, it&amp;#8217;s not always so great at keeping them going or getting them growing. Expert guidance and advice can help small businesses unlock opportunities that can sustain their growth.&amp;#8221;</p>&amp;#10;</blockquote>&amp;#10;"><p>The Building our Industrial Strategy green paper has been <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/building-our-industrial-strategy" target="_blank">published by the Government</a>.&nbsp;</p><p>The paper sets out a plan to improve living standards and economic growth by increasing productivity and driving growth across the whole country.&nbsp;</p>
<p>To achieve these goals, the green paper sets out ten strategic pillars.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Two of these pillars – developing skills and supporting businesses to grow – are particularly relevant to AAT, &nbsp;which already plays an important role in both areas.</p>
<h3>Developing skills&nbsp;</h3>
<p>The green paper indicates that Government must help people and businesses to thrive by, “…ensuring everyone has the basic skills needed in a modern economy” and “…building a new system of technical education to benefit the half of young people who do not go to university.”</p>
<p>AAT has over 80,000 students of which approximately 16,000 are apprentices. AAT would like to see careers information, advice and guidance in schools and colleges improved so that all young people are aware of the different routes to a rewarding career rather than continuing with the narrow focus on a University education.</p>
<p>Suzie Webb, Director of Education &amp; Development, AAT said: &nbsp;</p>
<blockquote><p>“The publication of an industrial strategy is a welcome development. There are lots of practical ways in which Government could better help those young people who don’t go to University, but improving information advice and guidance in schools would certainly be the most effective. AAT has made a number of recommendations as to how to achieve this, and will continue to engage with Government to push these recommendations forward.”</p>
</blockquote>
<h3>Supporting businesses to grow</h3>
<p>The green paper highlights a desire to ensure businesses across the UK can access the finance and management skills they need to grow.&nbsp;</p>
<p>In addition to equipping tens of thousands of people with the necessary finance and accounting skills to make businesses successful, and having licensed accountants provide accounting and financial support services to over 400,000 small businesses, AAT recently launched <a href="http://www.informi.co.uk" target="_blank">informi</a> a web site that provides free practical advice and support for small businesses. This includes information ranging from marketing and HR to accessing finance and improving management skills.</p>
<p>Adam Harper, Director of Strategy and Professional Standards at AAT, said;</p>
<blockquote><p>“The Government is right to concentrate on supporting businesses to start and grow. The UK already has a great track record at setting up new businesses, it’s not always so great at keeping them going or getting them growing. Expert guidance and advice can help small businesses unlock opportunities that can sustain their growth.”</p>
</blockquote>
</div>
            
          </div>
